#Describe the data
#Inputs - dataframe name
def custom_describe(df):
    unique_count = []
    for x in df.columns:
        mode = df[x].mode().iloc[0]
        unique_count.append([x,
                             len(df[x].unique()),
                             df[x].isnull().sum(),
                             mode,
                             df[x][df[x]==mode].count(),
                             df[x].dtypes])
    print("Dataframe Dimension: {} Rows, {} Columns".format(*df.shape))
    return pd.DataFrame(unique_count, columns=["Column","Unique","Missing","Mode","Mode Occurence","dtype"]).set_index("Column").T

describe = custom_describe(df).T
display(describe.iloc[:,0:])

def plot_pie(column, chart_name='pie_name_not_provided') :
    
    # Churn
    trace1 = go.Pie(values  = churn[column].value_counts().values.tolist(),
                    labels  = churn[column].value_counts().keys().tolist(),
                    hoverinfo = "label+percent+name",
                    domain  = dict(x = [0,.48]),
                    name    = "Churn Customers",
                    marker  = dict(colors =  ['#003f5c', '#7a5195', '#ef5675', '#ffa600'],line = dict(width = 2,
                                               color = "rgb(243,243,243)")
                                  ),
                    hole    = .6
                   )
    # Retained
    trace2 = go.Pie(values  = retained[column].value_counts().values.tolist(),
                    labels  = retained[column].value_counts().keys().tolist(),
                    hoverinfo = "label+percent+name",
                    marker  = dict(line = dict(width = 2,
                                               color = "rgb(243,243,243)")
                                  ),
                    domain  = dict(x = [.52,1]),
                    hole    = .6,
                    name    = "Retained customers" 
                   )


    layout = go.Layout(dict(title = column.title() + " Distribution In Customer Attrition ",
                            plot_bgcolor  = "rgb(243,243,243)",
                            paper_bgcolor = "rgb(243,243,243)",
                            annotations = [dict(text = "Churned",
                                                font = dict(size = 13),
                                                showarrow = False,
                                                x = .20, y = .5),
                                           dict(text = "Retained",
                                                font = dict(size = 14),
                                                showarrow = False,
                                                x = .80,y = .5
                                               )
                                          ]
                           )
                      )
    data = [trace1,trace2]
    fig = go.Figure(data = data,layout = layout)
    plotly.offline.iplot(fig, show_link=False, config=dict(displaylogo=False, modeBarButtonsToRemove=['sendDataToCloud']))
    
    
    # Output as Html page div
    # Needs externally sourced Plotly JS code
    # The JS code if provided in the output
    # Make sure the plotly-latest-min.js file is in the same folder as the graph(Html page); to make it run
    if get_div_output == True:
        barplot = plotly.offline.plot(fig, 
                                config={'displayModeBar': False}, 
                                show_link=False, 
                                include_plotlyjs=False, 
                                output_type='div')


        html_string = '''
        <html>
            <head>
                <script src='plotly-latest.min.js'></script>
                <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://maxcdn.bootstrapcdn.com/bootstrap/4.0.0/css/bootstrap.min.css"
                integrity="sha384-Gn5384xqQ1aoWXA+058RXPxPg6fy4IWvTNh0E263XmFcJlSAwiGgFAW/dAiS6JXm" crossorigin="anonymous">
                <style>body{ margin:0 100; background:whitesmoke; }</style>
            </head>
            <body>
                ''' + barplot + '''
            </body>
        </html>'''

        with open('../Graphs/'+str(chart_name)+'.html', 'w') as f:
            f.write(html_string)

# Using histograms for this
#function  for histogram for customer attrition types
def histogram(column) :
    trace1 = go.Histogram(x  = churn[column],
                          histnorm= "percent",
                          name = "Churned Customers",
                          marker = dict(color = '#f95d6a', line = dict(width = .5,
                                                    color = "black"
                                                    )
                                        ),
                         opacity = .9 
                         ) 
    
    trace2 = go.Histogram(x  = retained[column],
                          histnorm = "percent",
                          name = "Retained customers",
                          marker = dict(color = 'royalblue',line = dict(width = .5,
                                              color = "black"
                                             )
                                 ),
                          opacity = .9
                         )
    
    data = [trace1,trace2]
    layout = go.Layout(dict(title =column.title() + " Distribution In Customer Attrition ",
                            plot_bgcolor  = "rgb(243,243,243)",
                            paper_bgcolor = "rgb(243,243,243)",
                            xaxis = dict(gridcolor = 'rgb(255, 255, 255)',
                                             title = column,
                                             zerolinewidth=1,
                                             ticklen=5,
                                             gridwidth=2
                                            ),
                            yaxis = dict(gridcolor = 'rgb(255, 255, 255)',
                                             title = "Percentage",
                                             zerolinewidth=1,
                                             ticklen=5,
                                             gridwidth=2
                                            ),
                           )
                      )
    fig  = go.Figure(data=data,layout=layout)
    
    fig = go.Figure(data = data,layout = layout)
    plotly.offline.iplot(fig, show_link=False, config=dict(displaylogo=False, modeBarButtonsToRemove=['sendDataToCloud']))

Creating Tenures Features¶

In [47]:
def create_sub_tenures(df) :
    # Tenure less than or equal to 12 months
    if df["tenure"] <= 12 :
        return "Tenure_0_12"
    # 13 to 24 months
    elif (df["tenure"] > 12) & (df["tenure"] <= 24 ):
        return "Tenure_13_24"
    # 25 months to 48 months
    elif (df["tenure"] > 24) & (df["tenure"] <= 48) :
        return "Tenure_25_48"
    # 49 months to 60 months
    elif (df["tenure"] > 48) & (df["tenure"] <= 60) :
        return "Tenure_49_60"
    # greater than 60 months
    elif df["tenure"] > 60 :
        return "Tenure_gt_60"
In [48]:
df["tenure_group"] = df.apply(lambda df:create_sub_tenures(df),
                                      axis = 1)

                label = 'Total Charges', values = df['TotalCharges']),
            dict(range = [0,1],
                label = 'Churn', values = df['Churn'].map(yes_no),
                ticktext = ['No', 'Yes'], tickvals = [0,1]),
        ])
    )
]

layout = go.Layout(
    paper_bgcolor = 'ghostwhite'
)

fig = go.Figure(data = data, layout = layout)
plotly.offline.iplot(fig, show_link=False, config=dict(displaylogo=False,
                 modeBarButtonsToRemove=['sendDataToCloud']))

# Output as Html page div

if get_div_output == True:
    barplot = plotly.offline.plot(fig, 
                            config={'displayModeBar': False},

            <style>body{ margin:0 100; background:whitesmoke; }</style>
        </head>
        <body>
            ''' + barplot + '''
        </body>
    </html>'''

    with open('../Graphs/paracoords.html', 'w') as f:
        f.write(html_string)
